sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE TOP SPOT AFTER WINNING THE INNINGS.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons scored four 38-point games on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by 39 points over two days to take top spot in the county championship.

However, their stay at the top may be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey all came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in a rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.

After Somerset were driven out by 83 points at Grace Road on the first morning, Leicestershire extended their first goal with 94 points before being driven out by 296 points, with England's Andy Caddick taking three points for 83.
"Somerset, trailing by 213 points, started the second wicket strongly before Simmons stepped on the field and fired 174 points.
However, Essex look certain to regain top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such won their match against Yorkshire in Headingley.
Hussain, who is considered a surplus player in England's one-day teams, scored 158 goals, his first century of the season, when Essex scored 372 goals and led by 82 in the first half.

By the close Yorkshire had turned this into a 37-run advantage, but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes by taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on for 119 for five and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man whom England threw out, continued to silence his critics as he followed up his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out in Friday's match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England's hope Mark Butcher, who scored 70 points and Surrey finished with 429 points and a 234-point lead.
Derbyshire continued their hunt for their first title since 1936, reducing Worcestershire to 133 points on their second goal for fifth place and still 100 games away from avoiding defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody scored six goals (82), but Chris Adams (123) and Tim O'Gorman (109) led Derbyshire to 471 goals and a 233-goal lead.
After the disappointment that the start of the match was badly affected by the weather, Kent stepped up a gear and dismissed Nottinghamshire for 214.
They were stopped by Paul Johnson, who scored a well-deserved 84 points, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague scored four for 55 points.
By stumps, Kent reached 108 points for three.

The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was appointed England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million (US$23.4 million), replaces Tony Adams, who led the team at the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are injured and will miss England's World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer is on trial as captain, but new coach Glenn Hoddle has said he sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not take up the post.
"I'm sure there won't be any problems and I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," said Hoddle.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was willing and really wanted to do it.
"It's very difficult to come to a 100% conclusion about such a thing in four days...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he is aware of the team's situation, even though he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 partner Teddy Sheringham retired on Friday with an injury.
He will probably be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS LOCKED OUT AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

"Rotor Volgograd will have to play their next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during a 1-0 home defeat on Saturday, which ended Rotor's short period of league leadership.

The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that the team will be suspended on 3 September. "Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in empty stands on Saturday.
The club that knocked Manchester United out of the UEFA Cup last year is fined USD 1 000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in a good position in the championship with 11 matches left to play.
Volgograd is three points behind Alania and two behind Dinamo Moscow, but has a game in hand on the leaders and two on Moscow.
BOXING - PANAMANIAN BOXER ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
On Saturday, Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran climbs into the ring for another attempt to extend his long career.
Duran, 45, will take on little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in Panama.
This fight, Duran's first in his home country in 10 years, is being called "The Return of a Legend" here, and Duran still speaks as if he were in the prime of his life.
This match is for me to prepare.
I'm not going to retire," Duran told Reuters.
However, people close to the boxer admit that the title of champion in four different weight categories - lightweight, welterweight, middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the final frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could undermine his status as one of the best boxers in the world", said Ramon Manzanares, President of the Panama Boxing Association.
Duran, whose 97-12 record stretches back three decades, is hoping that a victory in the 10-round fight will give him the win over Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho won a controversial points decision over the Panamanian in the title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN WAS TWICE VICTORIOUS UNDER THE LIGHTS IN SPRING.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalists MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were unlucky on a night of adversity at the US Open tennis championships.
Wimbledon's miracle comeback could not be repeated by Washington's 11th seed, who lost 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 to hot wild-card Alex O'Brien in a two-hour and 51-minute battle on the Stadium Court.
In the next grandstand, 10th seed Rios lost to another Wimbledon-related player, the villain Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although sixth seed Agassi, the former champion, had to climb out of a dangerous 3:6 0:4 hole after winning 18 of the last 19 games against Leander Paes of India.
But the evening belonged to the "newcomers".
Washington, who came back from 1:5 down in the Wimbledon semi-final against Todd Martin to drop two sets in the third set, looked ready for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title in New Haven two weeks ago, went ahead 5-4 in the third set and Washington bounced back.
"I just kept telling myself: 'Give yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen'," said 26-year-old O'Brien, ranked 65th.
"I kept calm and I'm proud of myself for that - normally I would have folded my tent and gone home."
The hard-defending O'Brien, a former US Student National Team champion, scored 17 aces to finally beat Washington.
The fifth set continued until the sixth game, when Washington saved one break point with a forehand winner at the line, then backhanded a forehand winner to put O'Brien ahead 4:2.
The Texan scored two aces to hold his serve (5:2) and then, after another backhand from 40:0 by Washington, he converted the eighth point and won the match.
"You just keep fighting and try to get him to play a bit.
"I think he was a little tense at some points," Washington said. "
But I think he was a great help when needed. "

Tarango, who was fined USD 28 000 and banned from this year's All-England Club for a tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago, argued over calls and teased fans during a two-hour and 24-minute live tango with Rios in the stands.
A boisterous section of fans supported the distracted Chilean and shouted at the American, who had all the attention.
"I am an emotional player," said Tarango, ranked 104th. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match was decided in the third set, which the American won 7:5 to the horror of the crowd.
"I like a crowd, if it's there every day.
That's what drives me and makes me play my best tennis," said Tarango.
"I played my best tennis in college when the fraternities used to ply me with beer.
If tennis was like this every day, I think it would be much more fun for everyone. "
"He always complains too much," said Rios. "
But I don't think that's the reason.
I think I played very badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
The balls were flying very fast.
I lost too many points, which I never lose.
"I don't see the ball the way I see the day.
I play American, so I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango sarcastically kissed the crowd and then greeted the Rios supporters with a chuckle.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the supporters. "
At the same time, they openly rejoice before me.
After I won, I thought I could surprise them a bit. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL - RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leading defender and one of the most athletic players ever to play at centre-forward, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham, a three-time Pro Bowl selection, gained 4,482 yards on 677 passes.
"I'd like to thank the Eagles organisation and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for their support throughout my career," said Cunningham.
"Although I'm sad to leave, I'm looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been put on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in the history of the NFL," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall has been a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and has provided many great moments for fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
In 1985, Cunningham was selected in the second round and completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed a contract with the broadcaster.
